an\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབཏང་ཡོད་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབརྒྱབ་ཡོད་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབྱས་ཡོད་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབཏང་བཞག་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབརྒྱབ་བཞག་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབྱས་བཞག་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབཏང་ཡོད་རེད་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབརྒྱབ་ཡོད་རེད་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd width=\"195\" valign=\"top\"\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབྱས་ཡོད་རེད་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\n\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eNote: The egophoric auxiliaries and the perfect auxiliaries are not compatible with all verbs. For example, for a verb such as \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eསྐད་བཏང་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;to call,\u0026rdquo; depending on context it is possible to use either the intentional auxiliary or the receptive auxiliary: \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eསྐད་བཏང་པ་ཡིན།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;I called,\u0026rdquo; \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eསྐད་བཏང་བྱུང་།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;I was called (by someone).\u0026rdquo; On the other hand, for a non-volitional verb such as \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eརྨི་ལམ་བཏང་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;to dream,\u0026rdquo; the intentional auxiliary is incorrect *\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eརྨི་ལམ་བཏང་པ་ཡིན།\u003c/span\u003e and instead the receptive auxiliary must be used \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eརྨི་ལམ་བཏང་བྱུང་།\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eSome verbs can take a complement in the form of a direct or an indirect object, whereas others cannot. The verbalizer gives no indication as to whether a verb is \u0026ldquo;transitive\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;intransitive.\u0026rdquo; The following verbs all take an object:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཁོས་(རྒྱ་སྐད་)སློབ་སྦྱོང་བྱས་པ་རེད།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;He studied (Chinese).\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཁོས་(གློག་ལས་འཁྲུལ་འཁོར་)བེད་སྤྱོད་བྱས་པ་རེད།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;He used (the computer).\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eདགེ་རྒན་གྱིས་(སློབ་མ་)སྐད་བཏང་སོང་།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;The teacher called (the student).\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eང་ལ་(ཁྱེད་རང་)རྨི་ལམ་བཏང་བྱུང་།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;I dreamed (about you).\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eདགེ་རྒན་གྱིས་(གནས་ཚུལ་)ངོ་སྤྲོད་ཞུས་སོང་།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;The teacher presented (the situation).\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཁོང་གིས་(ཆོས་)ཉམས་ལེན་ཞེ་པོ་ཅིག་བྱེད་ཀྱི་འདུག་ག\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;He practices (the Dharma) a lot!\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eUnlike the verb \u0026ldquo;to study,\u0026rdquo; the verb \u0026ldquo;to work\u0026rdquo; is not transitive, and we can\u0026rsquo;t say: *\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཁོས་(ཤིང་)ལས་ཀ་བྱས་པ་རེད།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;He worked the wood.\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eNote\u003c/em\u003e: Several \u0026ldquo;intransitive\u0026rdquo; compound verbs take an ergative construction, whereas in the case of \u0026ldquo;simple\u0026rdquo; verbs this construction occurs only with transitive verbs. This may be explained by the fact that the noun that precedes the verbalizer can be assimilated to an \u0026ldquo;internal\u0026rdquo; object. In other words, the verbalizer acts as if it were an autonomous transitive verb.\u003c/p\u003e","source_url":null,"is_primary":true,"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:23 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:23 UTC","authors":[{"id":"6","fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre"}]}]}